how we can generate the revenue we need to support artists

The other factor was that Hollywood was coming. I knew
the film industry was going to come back to New York
because it was this cyclical thing film and television did, and
I had been reading up on that. And I said, "Whoa, wouldn't it
be really wild for productions not to have to go to Queens and
get caught in all that fucking traffic?" My daughter was an
actress, so I had to go to Silvercup. What if there was a studio
right here in Manhattan with facilities and expertise that
could compete with the studios in Queens? We had this huge
space on Broadway, and I negotiated an option to purchase
the building when it was time to renew our lease.
TG How did you support Just Above Midtown? Can you be
specific?
LGB Credit cards.
TG Okay. Where was the money coming from?
LGB Credit card debt. Yeah, I didn't have any money. I didn't
come from money. I didn't make money. Credit card debt.
On one level, it's obscene to pay interest, but that was the
resource I had. I could accumulate debt.
TO At that time, did you think there were no other options?
When JAM was a nonprofit, did you try fundraising?
LGB Yes, we did, and we threw event-based fundraisers, espe-
cially at Franklin Street. But as you and anyone who's worked
in the nonprofit sector knows, you need individual donors
who become loyal to you and support your organization over
time. But that wasn't even a concept for me. State and federal
grants, while we got them-that shit's determined by the
whims of politicians, and precarious. I don't want my shit to
be built on those whims. If we're going to put all our energy
in this, let's create something that has value a hundred years
from now. What are we creating that can evolve over the next
hundred years, support itself, and make life more equitable
for all of us?
TO JAM at 503 Broadway closed in 1986. What prompted
that?
LGB A number of things coalesced from different interest
groups that led ultimately to JAM's closing as a physical
space. The first was that the realtors and developers who
were developing Broadway were really upset because I was
renting out space at a lower per-square-foot rate than the
rate they charged. So they started complaining to the IRS
and saying, "It's unfair competition," because I could get
grants to subsidize and lower rent, and that was limiting their
ability to compete. These were people who had multiple
buildings. Why is this intimidating to you? How could you
be interested in twenty-five thousand square feet when you
own entire buildings?
The IRS came in and said, "Are you renting space?" And
I naively responded, "Yeah." I didn't see what the problem
was until they went, "It was not in your incorporation papers.
You do art; you can't rent real estate." That became a battle.
The other thing was that we had made the space so beautiful
that the landlords said they wanted me to renovate the whole
building. I looked at them and I went, "Excuse me, that's not
what I do. I do art." Along the way, I got an attorney and went
back to them to propose that they let us defer rent and use
the money for renovations and build a vested interest that
way. They agreed, but they wouldn't put it in writing. They
used the excuse that they didn't speak English.
